richTextContent.insert: These tables show which is the slowest class and method for each type of Apex, for all time (Left) and for the most recent day (Right). It is recommended to look at average run time across the different types of Apex because they have different use-cases, expectations, and performance thresholds.

For example, most executions would occur under 'Synchronous', which means a user performs an action and has to wait for that execution to finish before their page reloads or they navigate onwards. For this reason, a performance threshold of 5 seconds is important. For Batch Apex, there isn't neccessarily a time limit since it runs in the background. However, long-running Batch Apex may indicate sub-optimal code and could delay other batch jobs that are scheduled behind it in the queue.

richTextContent.insert: Not sure what the data in this dashboard means? Make sure to read the:

title.subtitleLabel: Breakdown of Run Time into its constituent parts

richTextContent.insert: The chart on the right helps understand what parts of the Apex execution are contributing towards overall time (RunTime).

Since RunTime is the sum of CPU, Execution, DB (Database) and Callout time, plotting the average times separately means that any significant spike in RunTime should be seen in one of the corresponding times. For example, a spike in RunTime could be accompanied by a spike in DB Time, which means there were issues with SOQL queries no longer being optimised, either through a change in indexes, a change in the query itself, or a change in the data volume for the table(s) being queried..

If there are anomalies in the chart - sudden spikes - click on that peak datapoint to focus the dashboard on that particular time, and investigate the Class and Method details below (Entry Point) to see what were the slowest-performing methods at that point in time.
Note: When viewing the chart by minute, it is best to select a particular day (Date) using the filters at the top of the dashboard.

The Details Table is where you begin to decide what specific part of the codebase to investigate. If you have made several selections on the dashboard, you should have identified some code or a particular day during which performance was poor. Based on those selections, the details table displays all the fun and exciting details of each execution.

It is important that you review the Apex Execution Event Log manual (https://sfdc.co/ApexExecutions) to understand the log details. But here's a brief explainer: RUN_TIME is the total execution time. RUN_TIME is the sum of CPU_TIME, DB_TOTAL_TIME, EXEC_TIME and CALLOUT_TIME.

If RUN_TIME is higher than normal, see what metric is contributing most: if it is CPU_TIME or EXEC_TIME, that means there is some very complex logic (if statements, for loops, dynamic Apex) and will require a developer to investigate; if it is DB_TOTAL_TIME and there are a low NUMBER_SOQL_QUERIES, that means the few SOQL queries need to be optimised (https://sfdc.co/SOQLTuning), or, if the NUMBER_SOQL_QUERIES is high, it may mean there are repeated queries that could be served by Apex Caching; if CALLOUT_TIME is high, investigate the Apex Callout log type to investigate which URL endpoint was being contacted and adding to round-trip network time.

In summary: the class or method identified will help you identify which owner in the codebase to contact; the specific performance metric will inform you and them what skillset is needed to investigate the code further.
Note, actual investigation of the code, line-by-line, will require reproducing the issue and investigating the Debug Logs.
Worst Performers Most Recent Day, By Type (QUIDDITY)
[General Note: this dashboard is interactive: click on a chart point or table row to narrow-down the investigation to specific point to investigate further.]

This is a chart of average Run Time (total execution time) for all classes and methods. We use a general Warning level of 3 seconds, and a Critical level of 5 seconds. Any days that see an average Run Time cross these thresholds warrants an investigation. Select any of the Class or Method rows in the summary table below or the Worst Performers tables above to see a trend of how that specific Class or Method performed over time. If any of the thresholds are reached, use the Execution Details table at the bottom of the dashboard to investigate further.
Note: When viewing the chart by minute, it is best to select a particular day (Date) using the filters at the top of the dashboard.

richTextContent.insert: This table shows the change in average run-time between the last two days, and the last day to the last 30 days.  Numbers less than 100% are good (green); over 100% is bad (red).

An increase in Daily Δ (> 100%) means yesterday was bad compared to the day before (it was over 100% of the previous day's run-time). An increase over 100% of the 30 Day Δ means yesteday was worse than the average of the last 30 days. The average execution time is also split-up into it's component times to determine where the issue is: Run Time is the overall time. Execution Time is logic (for loops, if statements, etc). CPU Time is the time to process in our app server. Database Time is time accessing the database (SOQL queries, etc). Callout Time is time spent waiting for HTTP requests made within Apex.

Understanding where performance time is poorest determines what skill set is needed to investigate: reducing Execution times requires general coding skills; Database time requires a skillset in SOQL query optimisation or Apex Caching; Callout time may require involving owners of the network or endpoint that Apex is making requests to.
Worst Performers Of All Time, By Type (QUIDDITY)
The Summary Data Table is a way to begin analysing a class or method that is either a frequently used piece of code, is known to be criticial to the business, or consisently performs poorly.
Total Count: the number of executions.
Avg Time: the average run-time for all executions.
Avg Time >5s: of the executions that were 'slow', what their average run-time was.
The columns are sortable: sort by Total Count to analyse the most common code; by Avg Time to find the slowest; by % to find the most commonly slow.
Click on a particular number (not the class or method name) to view all of the execution details in the Details Table below.

This chart shows the total number of apex executions over time (blue), and what percentage of those executions were 'slow' (red). Slow is traditionally defined as any Apex code that takes longer than 5 seconds to complete.

Both chart lines should have the same shape: if the total number of Apex executions is consistent over time, then proportionally the number of 'slow' executions should be consistent over time, also. If the total number of executions increases significantly, it's expected that un-optimised code will under-perform and contribute to the 'slow' executions.

If slow executions increases dramatically while the total number of executions stays consistent, it is likely that a new issue has arisen: new or changed code, large data volumes; there are many factors that can contribute to poor performance.
Note: When viewing the chart by minute, it is best to select a particular day (Date) using the filters at the top of the dashboard.
